title: Grateful Dead Live at Alpine Valley Music Theatre on 1988-06-23
description: Iko Iko, Minglewood Blues, It Must Have Been The Roses, Me & My Uncle-> Mexicali Blues, Stagger Lee, When I Paint My Masterpiece, Bird Song, Promised Land Hey Pocky Way, Believe It Or Not, Women Are Smarter, He's Gone-> Drums-> Jam-> I Need A Miracle-> Gimme Some Lovin'-> All Along The Watchtower-> Morning Dew, E:Blackbird-> E: Brokedown Palace

reviews.review_text: Can't believe I didn't stick around for this one!!!! Damn.  What was I thinking?...drove up from Chicago for the 22nd....and drove back the next day....and missed this killer show!  I'm only 2/3 of the way through listening to it...but I know I'll be burning it TODAY and putting it in the truck CD changer..... what is it about Alpine Valley?  Jerry does some sweeet work on this night!  Being blown away as I type.....that's right...the women are smarter!

You need this if... ...you're a fan of 'Believe It' As rare as the song was, they never equalled this one.  Crooning Jerry at his best.  And the 'Dew' is just EPIC -- a MUST have.  I put it up there with the all time best of the best.  The audience reaction gives you some idea of how great it must have been to be there.  A friend who attended swears it had many folks in tears.

I was there After 3 awsome Alpine shows...I can't recommend the 6/20 show any higher, we were spent but the Dew and the acoustic Blackbird capped off the best tour roadtrip ever.  For those in the know...the Goony Birds were insane.

goony birds aaah yes...

to be 18 again

my 3rd show

and 1st taste of ellis d
Hey Pocky Way Check out the Pocky Way scat by Brent...yea.

Beautiful Show Listen to the Blackbird>Brokedown. Everyone was laughing at the messed-up Blackbird and the joy that created made everyone cry into Brokedwon - you can esp. hear it in Jerry.

Oh, and the Gooney Birds were stellar in the Summer of '88  !!!
Solstice jams I must admit, Brent's vocals and playing on Pocky Way are "the bomb", plus Jerry fills it in with some tight licks.  The alpine shows were always dead head friendly. Thanks East Troy!

pitch problems i just finished slowing this show down to proper pitch. i will upload the speed corrected file as soon as i figure out how. this is a very enjoyable show so if you are gonna download it, you might want to hold off until i get the corrected show uploaded to the archive.
Music is such a powerful emotion. If you are a Dead fan and don't get choked up during  Blackbird

Last of the 4 shows from Alpine '88 These shows range quite a bit in tightness, but don't let that stop you from enjoying them all.  Each one is different. I always amazes me how much the GD can change from one night to the next.  

This particular show is nice. It smooth, but there's the occasional edge, without as much of the "fallout" that comes to mind with the 80's and 90's shows.  Pocky Way and Roses both stand out.  

Once again, thanks to the Grateful Dead AND the Archive for making all this possible.

Oneof my favorites This has always been one of my favorites, not in a '73, '74 kind of way.  But when I want to hear something light with energy this is the show I usually turn to.
Love Brent's Hey Pokey Way and Gimme Some Lovin.
Nice Blackbird.

At the time of this show I was taking a break from shows.  My dad was dying of cancer and just about gone.  A friend of gave a tape of this show that they had just been to and it really lifted my spirits.  Still does every time I hear it.
He's Gone really gets me.

Thank you Grateful Dead.

The "Golden Era" Having just read the book on The GD's equipment (a must read BTW), I read a great line that called the mid-ish to late-80's the GD's "Golden Era".  It couldn't be more true.

I was in a marriage doomed to failure, a daughter, and in love with music as an escape.  A friend went with me to this show and later told me he had a lump in his throat during Morning Dew.  He had never seen the Dead and had only heard Jeff Beck's Morning Dew in the past.

Jerry's voice is far from "perfect" but the soul and emotion are unbelieveable.  I think this show also showcased what an extraordinary person Brent was and how much he musically added to the band.  It was a shame how he was not appreciated at the onset of his GD career.

I love this show as I do all late 80's Alpine shows.  Truly a Golden Era of newly found inspriation, musical achievement, and emotion.  Check it out my friend.

out of sync? i don't know fellow travelers. after standing on the lawn with a head full of silly-cyben all those years ago and now checking it out closely--the band seems out of sync/lifeless for much of this.garcia's timing on all levels is not there. weir can't get off stage quickly enough after the first set. women r' smarter begins with a clam.need a miracle comes out of the gate flat and stays that way.ditto for gimme some lovin.the watchtower transition begins with another clam. jerry digs down deep and rescues things with a pretty nice morning dew.the encores were charming.
Average Totally average with a decent set list

a special show for me Overall: A much more solid night than the night before.  This was my favorite night of the run.  Healey was apparently adding a stupid flange effects the vocals (and instruments at times), but if you listen to this audience recording it actually kind of fits with the acoustics created by that huge Alpine roof (on the SBD of this show, the flange is more pronounced).  It definitely takes away from the peformance, but it's not horrible and you get used to it, plus its not as prominent in the second set.  Aside from that, the song selection is really fantastic and the playing is mostly solid and at times great.  One interesting note - Bobby loses his place rhythmically several times during this show, either falling one beat ahead or behind the song (Masterpiece, Bird Song, Women R, etc.), which cracks me up.  4 stars for the show, but only 3 b/c this recording isn't too great (but still my thanks for uploading it for us all to enjoy).  

The scene: the dust bowl coming to a close.  After the show, Frank and I split ASAP and drove all night to get back for our high school graduation.  I used to have a funny picture of Frank with his head back against the passenger seat of the bus, asleep, and a really beautiful sunrise in the background.  The school didn't want to let us participate in the graduation ceremony, ostensibly because we hadn't attended the rehearsal.  In reality, they were just pissed because we skipped half our finals to go to these Alpine shows, but our grades were still good enough to graduate (that really ticked them off).  But this night brought to a close our first run of Alpine shows and was special for me in a few different ways.  

The music: Set I: A decent Aiko is always a good way to start an evening.  Roses is just rare enough to be special (I seem to recall never hearing it more than once a tour) and this is a beautiful version, even with Healey's vocal effects.  Masterpiece>Bird Song>Promised Land is one of my favorite first set song blocks.  The jam on this Bird Song is definitely unique, although it rides that fine line between disjointed and "out there."  

Set II: Hey Pockey Way continues the outstanding song selection for the evening, and Brent's working hard to get you off your ass and shake that thang.  Believe it or Not continues the nightly new song parade for this Alpine run.  I think this song faded away soon after its debut because Standing on the Moon (which debuted less than a year later) sort of had a similar vibe and it was, frankly, a better song.  Women R Smarter gets everybody dancing again, with some nice moments from Brent.  He's Gone was really special for me this night.  On the day we left for Alpine our friend Nick died in a car accident.  Frank and I didn't find out until the 21st when we called some friends to give them the set list updates for the first couple of shows.  So when they started playing this, I sat over by the little group of trees on the far Phil side and cried a little.  I'd known Nick since elementary school, but only been friends with him the last couple of years - mostly because he lived in the same neighborhood as Bill P, so we all wound up hanging out.  The week after Alpine, he was supposed to move into the apartment on Alliance Ave (with Aaron, Larry, and Jaime) that I moved into that fall when I got back from fall tour.  This is a decent version with a somber little jam afterward.  Drums has a lot of intresting sounds and instrumentation on this evening.  Miracle>GSL>Watchtower is another favorite song-block of mine and this one is played really well.  Dew is awesome.  Jerry really wails out some lyrics and Phil churns out some big chords at one point as well.  There are two very nice peaks to it.  Blackbird encore??  This one blew me away.  It had some really special meaning for me personally because I was embarcing on my first full tour, I was graduating from high school with so much ahead of me, and this was my first trip in the new VW that would be my home periodically for a few years while out on the road.  In sum, I "was only waiting for this moment to arrive."  This was the first of only two "attempts" at Blackbird (they screwed up both pretty well).  It was a complete surprise to me at the time, but astute listeners might not have been so surprised.  At the beginning of the second set on 4/8/88 Jerry played a full couple of lines of this song before they started the set.  Brokedown is always my favorite of the slow-tune encores.  To this day it still reminds me of falling asleep with my walkman on as a 15 year-old kid listening to Dead Set.

One Of The Best I Went To I went to all four of the Apine Valley Shows in 1988. I also did the summer tour from Buckeye Lake to Pittsburgh to Rochester, Saratoga to Maine. This show I had an amazing experience!
I felt such love during this show. I really felt
God came to me so strongly and showed me His love. I felt a strong unity with the people that night.  The music just sounded better than the other three nights.

Ridin' thru the valley Having not really explored '88, this came as a grateful surprise. It's not five star but it has got alot of positive energy and that's the most important thing. The song list has personal favourites (When I Paint My Masterpiece, Stagger Lee, Mornin' Dew...) and a couple of welcome unusual additions; Believe It Or Not and the fun/funny/messy Blackbird. Jerry's voice is strong and clear throughout. What was Weir on?! Overall, four stars for a fun ride thru the Alpine valley. Enjoy!
